<node CREATED="1388396224022" ID="_" MODIFIED="1388396251882" TEXT="pros and cons of maven3 and gradle as I experience them so far">
<node CREATED="1388396255055" ID="Freemind_Link_412755107" MODIFIED="1388399029031" TEXT="My experience level in maven 3 and gradle differ."/>
<node CREATED="1388396283000" ID="Freemind_Link_1263985190" MODIFIED="1388396376527" TEXT="gradle api&apos;s is undergoing significant change from one minor version to the next"/>
<node CREATED="1388396381275" ID="Freemind_Link_153019429" MODIFIED="1388396464394" TEXT="mvn convention and implementation makes it hard to use otherwise reasonable ideas">
<node CREATED="1388396465406" ID="Freemind_Link_1015909070" MODIFIED="1388396517004" TEXT="separate unit test and integrations test into different folder structures"/>
<node CREATED="1388396517560" ID="Freemind_Link_1993377803" MODIFIED="1388396556269" TEXT="implement tests using groovy"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1388396631516" ID="Freemind_Link_1046074181" MODIFIED="1388396675634" TEXT="gradle lacks the &quot;good gut feeling&quot; of maven">
<node CREATED="1388396676190" ID="Freemind_Link_1353692563" MODIFIED="1388397540306" TEXT="If it works in maven, I&apos;m walking on mine-free territory"/>
<node CREATED="1388396745000" ID="Freemind_Link_1835892264" MODIFIED="1388396916250" TEXT="even if I can make it work with gradle, it doesn&apos;t necessarily mean that I&apos;m doing it &quot;right&quot;"/>
<node CREATED="1388397241672" ID="Freemind_Link_1240558491" MODIFIED="1388397481488" TEXT="I fear ending up in ant-hell, where a buildfile complex can be unmaintainable for new project members, or even for yourself - if you have been busy doing other projects for a couple of months."/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1388398084859" ID="Freemind_Link_778683994" MODIFIED="1388398084862" TEXT="several of the tasks that were hard in maven is pleasantly easy in gradle &#xa;">
<node CREATED="1388398095291" ID="Freemind_Link_1515330808" MODIFIED="1388398121231" TEXT="mixing java and groovy"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1388397942492" ID="Freemind_Link_1704315207" MODIFIED="1388398286405" TEXT="maven, being as mature as it is, has articles with examples and &quot;headaches solved&quot; in plenty on the net"/>
<node CREATED="1388398323611" ID="Freemind_Link_378262798" MODIFIED="1388399011768" TEXT="The developers of gradle doesn&apos;t seem to fully appreciate the qualities of maven, discarding simple conventions such as the results of a build being stored in the build folder as opposed to the target folder and letting the .gradle folder survive a gradle clean, and letting the .settings folder survive a gradle cleanEclipse. Of course you can customize your build file to behave like maven in these respects, but it adds &quot;mud&quot; to the build files - exactly the opposite to what you want to achieve when migrating from maven to gradle."/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1388396917318" ID="Freemind_Link_1132704750" MODIFIED="1388397052355" TEXT="maybe you should aim for your gradle build files to be short, conventional and immediately readable, in order to keep the good gut feeling."/>
<node CREATED="1388397055179" ID="Freemind_Link_1766374790" MODIFIED="1388397184327" TEXT="gradle build file hacking is for people who perceive maven&apos;s structure and convention features as being a hindrance rather than a help"/>
<node CREATED="1388397562616" ID="Freemind_Link_327197571" MODIFIED="1388406866142" TEXT="for the rest of us, we get to enjoy white-space instead of angled brackets in our build files"/>
<node CREATED="1388407087290" ID="Freemind_Link_1045109482" MODIFIED="1388407476880" TEXT="I warmly recommend the upcoming book &quot;Gradle in Action&quot; by Benjamin Muschko, it was a great help in creating the gradle build files used in this example. You can get access to a preliminary version under Manning&apos;s Early Access Program (MEAP)"/>
<node CREATED="1388406869042" ID="Freemind_Link_87466394" MODIFIED="1388407060501" TEXT="Thanks to Roger Goosen, Ken Kousen, MKYoung for sharing their knowledge and experience. Thanks to Abhay Agarwal for a constructive and pedagogical answer to Monica. Shiralkars Coderanch question."/>
</node>
</node>
